definition.value: A sialodiosylceramide in which a 4-acetylated 5-glycosylated sialic acid residue is linked to the ceramide moiety by a beta-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-glucosyl chain.
An androstanoid having a double bond at C-5, an oxo group at C-3 and a hydroxy group with beta-configuration at C-17.
An aldehyde that is acetaldehyde in which one of the methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a methylsulfanyl group.
A member of the class of acetamides resulting from the formal condensation of the amino group of 1-phenylethylamine with 1 mol eq. of acetic acid.
An amino dicarboxylic acid that is 4-aminohepta-2,4-dienoic acid which is substituted at position 6 by an oxo group [the (2Z,4E) isomer].

An organic heterotricyclic compound and tetramic acid derivative isolated from a mutant strain of Saccharothrix syringae. Nocamycin E exhibits considerably lower antibacterial activity than the corresponding methyl ester, nocamycin I.
A sulfoxide resulting from the oxidation of the thiourea sulfur group of diafenthiuron.

A branched oligosaccharide derivative consisting of nine residues corresponding to the core region of Salmonella lipopolysaccharide molecules and used as a model compound in investigations on the conjugation of the O-antigen to the CRM197 carrier protein. (It should be noted that the site and degree of phosphorylation of the Hep(III) residue are uncertain, while for the PPEtN group the percentage substitution can vary according to the strain of origin and the growth conditions.)
An N-hydroxysuccinimide ester formed from adipic acid.

An L-alpha-amino acid residue in which  L-alpha-D-Hepp4PPEtN is conjugated to the epsilon position of an L-lysine residue via a SIDEA linker. One of a number of structurally modified lysine residues arising from deglycosylation with trifluoromethanesulfonic acid (TFMS) of the core region of Salmonella conjugated with the carrier protein CRM197.
A hex-2-en-1-ol that has (E)-configuration.

An L-alpha-amino acid residue in which PPEtN is conjugated to the epsilon position of an L-lysine residue via a SIDEA linker. One of a number of structurally modified lysine residues arising from deglycosylation with trifluoromethanesulfonic acid (TFMS) of the core region of Salmonella conjugated with the carrier protein CRM197.

An L-alpha-amino acid residue in which PEtN is conjugated to the epsilon position of an L-lysine residue via a SIDEA linker. One of a number of structurally modified lysine residues arising from deglycosylation with trifluoromethanesulfonic acid (TFMS) of the core region of Salmonella conjugated with the carrier protein CRM197.

An L-alpha-amino acid residue in which HOEtN is conjugated to the epsilon position of an L-lysine residue via a SIDEA linker. One of a number of structurally modified lysine residues arising from deglycosylation with trifluoromethanesulfonic acid (TFMS) of the core region of Salmonella conjugated with the carrier protein CRM197.
An acetate ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of (E)-hex-2-en-1-ol with the carboxy group of acetic acid.
An acetate ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of nerol with the carboxy group of acetic acid.
The anion formed by loss of a proton from the carboxy group of (R)-3-hydroxyisobutyric acid; major microspecies at pH 7.3.
2-methyl-3-oxopropanoate with R configuration at the chiral centre; major microspecies at pH 7.3.

A member of the class of isoxazoles that is 1,2-oxazole substituted by a 2-(methanesulfonyl)-4-(trifluoromethyl)benzoyl group and a cyclopropyl group at positions 4 and 5, respectively. It is a 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate dioxygenase inhibitor which is used as a herbicide for weed control in maize and sugarcane.
A beta-diketone and nitrile resulting from the the degradation of the isoxazole ring of isoxaflutole. The active herbicide of the proherbicide isoxaflutole.
The furanose form of D-apiose.
A member of the class of toluenes that is toluene in which the hydrogens at positions 3 and 5 have been replaced by methoxy groups. It is the major scent compound of many rose varieties.
A germacrane sesquiterpenoid that is germacrene D in which the exocyclic double bond has undergone formal addition of water to afford the corresponding tertiary alcohol.

A triazolopyridazine that is tetrahydro-1H-[1,2,4]triazolo[1,2-a]pyridazine which is substituted at positions 1, 3, and 4 by oxo, sulfanyl  and 4-chloro-2-fluoro-5-[(2-methoxy-2-oxoethyl)sulfanyl]phenyl groups, respectively. The active metabolite of the proherbicide fluthiacet-methyl.
A sesquiterpenoid that is isopropanol which is substituted at position 2 by a (3S,4S)-3-isopropenyl-4-methyl-4-vinylcyclohexyl group.
An ocimene that consists of octa-2,4,6-triene bearing methyl substituents at positions 2 and 6 (the 4E,6E-isomer).
